<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <title>{{ title }}</title>
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
</head>
<body>
<header>
  <h1>{{ title }}</h1>
  <p>
    Endpoint documentation for <code>{{ service_url }}</code> in the
    CBRWS web service.
  </p>
</header>

<main>
  <section>
    <h2>What This Endpoint Does</h2>
    <p>
      The greeting endpoint (<code>{{ service_url }}</code>) returns
      a JSON greeting message. It is the simplest resource in the
      CBRWS web service and a good starting point for understanding
      how the API works.
    </p>
    <p>
      The endpoint accepts <code>GET</code>, <code>HEAD</code>, and
      <code>OPTIONS</code> requests. All other HTTP methods (such as
      <code>POST</code>, <code>PUT</code>, or <code>DELETE</code>)
      are rejected with an error.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Discovering the Endpoint</h2>
    <p>
      You do not need to hardcode the greeting endpoint URL into your
      client. Instead, you can discover it by first requesting the API
      discovery document at <code>{{ api_url }}</code>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The discovery document is a JSON object that lists the resources
      available in the API. Each resource appears as a link with a URL
      (<code>href</code>) and metadata. The greeting endpoint appears
      under the key <code>cbrws:greeting</code> inside the
      <code>_links</code> object:
    </p>
    <pre><code>GET {{ api_url }}

{
  "title": "CBRWS API",
  "version": "1.0",
  "_links": {
    ...
    "cbrws:greeting": {
      "href": "{{ service_url }}",
      "type": "{{ service_media_type }}",
      "profile": "{{ schema_url }}"
    }
  }
}</code></pre>
    <p>
      The key <code>cbrws:greeting</code> is a shorthand called a
      CURIE (Compact URI). The prefix <code>cbrws:</code> is defined
      in a <code>curies</code> array in the same document. Expanding
      the CURIE gives you the full URL of this documentation page:
      <code>{{ schema_url }}</code>. You do not need to expand CURIEs to
      use the API &mdash; they are simply a naming convention for link
      relations.
    </p>
    <p>
      To call the greeting endpoint, use the value of the
      <code>href</code> field: <code>{{ service_url }}</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Making a GET Request</h2>
    <h3>URL</h3>
    <p><code>{{ service_url }}</code></p>

    <h3>Method</h3>
    <p><code>GET</code></p>

    <h3>Request Headers</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Header</th>
          <th>Required</th>
          <th>Value</th>
          <th>Notes</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>Accept</code></td>
          <td>No</td>
          <td><code>{{ service_media_type }}</code></td>
          <td>
            If omitted, the server defaults to
            <code>{{ service_media_type }}</code>. Sending an
            unsupported value (such as <code>application/xml</code>)
            produces a <code>406 Not Acceptable</code> error.
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Request Body</h3>
    <p>
      None. <code>GET</code> requests to this endpoint do not accept
      a request body.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Successful Response (200 OK)</h2>

    <h3>Response Headers</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Header</th><th>Value</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>Content-Type</code></td>
          <td><code>{{ service_media_type }}</code></td>
          <td>
            The response body is JSON formatted using HAL (Hypertext
            Application Language). HAL is a convention for including
            navigation links inside JSON responses. If your client
            just needs the data fields, you can treat the response as
            ordinary JSON and ignore the <code>_links</code> object.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>Allow</code></td>
          <td><code>GET, HEAD, OPTIONS</code></td>
          <td>The HTTP methods this endpoint accepts.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>Link</code></td>
          <td>(multiple entries &mdash; see below)</td>
          <td>
            Machine-readable pointers to this documentation page and
            to the JSON Schema for the response.
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h4>The Link Header</h4>
    <p>
      The <code>Link</code> header contains three entries, all
      pointing to this documentation URL
      (<code>{{ schema_url }}</code>):
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Relation</th><th>Type</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>profile</code></td>
          <td>&mdash;</td>
          <td>
            Identifies the semantic profile (i.e. the contract) that
            this response conforms to. This is a standard mechanism
            (defined in RFC 6906) for a server to say &ldquo;the
            response you just received follows the rules described at
            this URL.&rdquo;
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>describedBy</code></td>
          <td><code>application/schema+json</code></td>
          <td>
            Points to a machine-readable JSON Schema that describes the
            structure of the response body. Request this URL with
            <code>Accept: application/schema+json</code> to retrieve
            the schema.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>documentation</code></td>
          <td><code>text/html</code></td>
          <td>
            Points to this human-readable HTML page. Request this URL
            with <code>Accept: text/html</code> or open it in a
            browser.
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Response Body</h3>
    <p>
      The response body is a JSON object with the following fields:
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Field</th>
          <th>Type</th>
          <th>Always Present</th>
          <th>Description</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>message</code></td>
          <td>string</td>
          <td>Yes</td>
          <td>
            The greeting message
            (e.g. <code>"Hello, world!"</code>).
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>_links</code></td>
          <td>object</td>
          <td>Yes</td>
          <td>
            Navigation links. See
            <a href="#understanding-the-links">Understanding the
            Links</a> below.
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h4>Example Response Body</h4>
    <pre><code>{
  "message": "Hello, world!",
  "_links": {
    "self": {
      "href": "{{ service_url }}",
      "type": "{{ service_media_type }}",
      "profile": "{{ schema_url }}"
    },
    "up": {
      "href": "{{ api_url }}",
      "type": "{{ service_media_type }}",
      "profile": "{{ api_schema_url }}"
    }
  }
}</code></pre>
  </section>

  <section id="understanding-the-links">
    <h2>Understanding the Links</h2>
    <p>
      The <code>_links</code> object is a HAL convention for embedding
      navigation links in a JSON response. Each key in
      <code>_links</code> is a <em>relation name</em> that describes
      how the linked resource relates to the current one. Think of
      them as the JSON equivalent of clickable links on a web page.
    </p>
    <p>
      You do not need to follow these links to use the greeting
      endpoint. They are provided so that a client can navigate the
      API programmatically without hardcoding URLs.
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Link</th>
          <th>What It Points To</th>
          <th>Why It Is Useful</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>self</code></td>
          <td>
            This endpoint:
            <code>{{ service_url }}</code>
          </td>
          <td>
            The canonical URL for this resource. A client can use it to
            refresh the resource or share a stable reference to it.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>up</code></td>
          <td>
            The API discovery document:
            <code>{{ api_url }}</code>
          </td>
          <td>
            The parent resource. Following this link takes you back to
            the API root, where you can discover other endpoints.
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>Each link object also contains:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <code>type</code> &mdash; the response media type of the
        linked resource
        (e.g. <code>{{ service_media_type }}</code>), telling your
        client what format to expect.
      </li>
      <li>
        <code>profile</code> &mdash; the URL of the documentation
        page that describes the linked resource&rsquo;s structure and
        meaning. Open this URL in a browser to read the documentation,
        or request it with
        <code>Accept: application/schema+json</code> to get a
        machine-readable schema.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Other Supported HTTP Methods</h2>

    <h3>HEAD</h3>
    <p>
      A <code>HEAD</code> request returns the same response headers as
      a <code>GET</code> request (including <code>Content-Type</code>,
      <code>Allow</code>, and <code>Link</code>) but with an empty
      body. Use this when you only need to check that the endpoint
      exists or to inspect its headers without downloading the full
      response.
    </p>

    <h3>OPTIONS</h3>
    <p>
      An <code>OPTIONS</code> request returns a
      <code>204 No Content</code> response with an
      <code>Allow</code> header listing the HTTP methods this endpoint
      accepts (<code>GET, HEAD, OPTIONS</code>) and a
      <code>Link</code> header. The response has no body. Use this to
      check which methods are available before making a request.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Error Responses</h2>
    <p>
      All error responses from this endpoint (and from the CBRWS web
      service in general) use the
      <code>application/problem+json</code> media type. This is a
      standard format defined in
      <a href="https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7807">RFC
      7807</a> (Problem Details for HTTP APIs) for reporting errors in
      a consistent, machine-readable way. Every error response is a
      JSON object with at least these fields:
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Field</th><th>Type</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>type</code></td>
          <td>string (URL)</td>
          <td>
            A URL that identifies the kind of error. You can open this
            URL in a browser for a general explanation of the HTTP
            status code.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>title</code></td>
          <td>string</td>
          <td>A short, human-readable name for the error.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>status</code></td>
          <td>integer</td>
          <td>
            The HTTP status code (matches the response status line).
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>detail</code></td>
          <td>string</td>
          <td>
            A human-readable explanation of what went wrong in this
            specific request.
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>405 Method Not Allowed</h3>
    <p>
      Returned when you use an HTTP method that this endpoint does not
      support (for example <code>POST</code>, <code>PUT</code>,
      <code>DELETE</code>, or <code>PATCH</code>). The response
      includes an <code>Allow</code> header listing the methods that
      are accepted, and an <code>allowedMethods</code> array in the
      body with the same information.
    </p>
    <pre><code>HTTP/1.1 405 Method Not Allowed
Content-Type: application/problem+json
Allow: GET, HEAD, OPTIONS

{
  "type": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Reference/Status/405",
  "title": "Method Not Allowed",
  "status": 405,
  "detail": "The requested method is not allowed for this resource. See the Allow header for allowed methods.",
  "allowedMethods": ["GET", "HEAD", "OPTIONS"]
}</code></pre>

    <h3>406 Not Acceptable</h3>
    <p>
      Returned when your <code>Accept</code> header asks for a media
      type that this endpoint cannot produce. The greeting endpoint
      only produces <code>{{ service_media_type }}</code>. If you
      request something else (such as <code>application/xml</code>),
      you will get this error. The response body lists the media types
      the endpoint supports in the <code>supportedMediaTypes</code>
      array.
    </p>
    <pre><code>HTTP/1.1 406 Not Acceptable
Content-Type: application/problem+json
Allow: GET, HEAD, OPTIONS

{
  "type": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Reference/Status/406",
  "title": "Not Acceptable",
  "status": 406,
  "detail": "The requested media type is not supported by this endpoint. Supported media types are: {{ service_media_type }}",
  "supportedMediaTypes": ["{{ service_media_type }}"]
}</code></pre>

    <h3>404 Not Found</h3>
    <p>
      Returned when you request a URL that does not exist on the
      server. If you receive this error when trying to reach the
      greeting endpoint, check that you are using the correct URL. The
      safest approach is to discover the URL from the API discovery
      document at <code>{{ api_url }}</code> rather than hardcoding it.
    </p>
    <pre><code>HTTP/1.1 404 Not Found
Content-Type: application/problem+json

{
  "type": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Reference/Status/404",
  "title": "Not Found",
  "status": 404,
  "detail": "The requested resource was not found on this server. Please check the URL and try again."
}</code></pre>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Examples Using curl</h2>
    <p>
      The examples below use
      <a href="https://curl.se/">curl</a>, a command-line tool for
      making HTTP requests. The <code>-s</code> flag silences
      progress output and <code>-D -</code> prints the response
      headers to the terminal alongside the body.
    </p>

    <h3>Fetch the Greeting</h3>
    <pre><code>curl -s -D - {{ service_url }}</code></pre>
    <p>Expected output:</p>
    <pre><code>HTTP/1.1 200 OK
content-type: {{ service_media_type }}
allow: GET, HEAD, OPTIONS
link: &lt;{{ schema_url }}&gt;; rel="profile"; ..., ...

{
  "message": "Hello, world!",
  "_links": {
    "self": {
      "href": "{{ service_url }}",
      "type": "{{ service_media_type }}",
      "profile": "{{ schema_url }}"
    },
    "up": {
      "href": "{{ api_url }}",
      "type": "{{ service_media_type }}",
      "profile": "{{ api_schema_url }}"
    }
  }
}</code></pre>

    <h3>Fetch with an Explicit Accept Header</h3>
    <pre><code>curl -s -D - -H "Accept: {{ service_media_type }}" {{ service_url }}</code></pre>
    <p>
      The response is identical to the previous example. Setting the
      <code>Accept</code> header explicitly is optional but good
      practice &mdash; it makes your client&rsquo;s expectations
      clear to both the server and to anyone reading your code.
    </p>

    <h3>Check Headers Only (HEAD)</h3>
    <pre><code>curl -s -D - --head {{ service_url }}</code></pre>
    <p>Expected output (headers only, no body):</p>
    <pre><code>HTTP/1.1 200 OK
content-type: {{ service_media_type }}
allow: GET, HEAD, OPTIONS
link: ...</code></pre>

    <h3>Check Allowed Methods (OPTIONS)</h3>
    <pre><code>curl -s -D - -X OPTIONS {{ service_url }}</code></pre>
    <p>Expected output:</p>
    <pre><code>HTTP/1.1 204 No Content
allow: GET, HEAD, OPTIONS
link: ...</code></pre>

    <h3>Trigger a 405 Method Not Allowed Error</h3>
    <pre><code>curl -s -D - -X POST {{ service_url }}</code></pre>
    <p>Expected output:</p>
    <pre><code>HTTP/1.1 405 Method Not Allowed
content-type: application/problem+json
allow: GET, HEAD, OPTIONS

{
  "type": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Reference/Status/405",
  "title": "Method Not Allowed",
  "status": 405,
  "detail": "The requested method is not allowed for this resource. See the Allow header for allowed methods.",
  "allowedMethods": ["GET", "HEAD", "OPTIONS"]
}</code></pre>

    <h3>Trigger a 406 Not Acceptable Error</h3>
    <pre><code>curl -s -D - -H "Accept: application/xml" {{ service_url }}</code></pre>
    <p>Expected output:</p>
    <pre><code>HTTP/1.1 406 Not Acceptable
content-type: application/problem+json
allow: GET, HEAD, OPTIONS

{
  "type": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Reference/Status/406",
  "title": "Not Acceptable",
  "status": 406,
  "detail": "The requested media type is not supported by this endpoint. Supported media types are: {{ service_media_type }}",
  "supportedMediaTypes": ["{{ service_media_type }}"]
}</code></pre>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>About This Documentation URL</h2>
    <p>
      You are reading a page served from
      <code>{{ schema_url }}</code>. This same URL also serves a
      machine-readable JSON Schema &mdash; which one you receive
      depends on the <code>Accept</code> header you send:
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th><code>Accept</code> Header</th>
          <th>What You Get</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>text/html</code> (or a browser)</td>
          <td>This page (human-readable documentation).</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>
            <code>application/schema+json</code> (or omitted)
          </td>
          <td>
            A JSON Schema document that formally describes the
            structure of the greeting endpoint response. You can use
            this schema with a JSON Schema validator library to verify
            that a response body has the expected shape.
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>To fetch the JSON Schema from the command line:</p>
    <pre><code>curl -s -H "Accept: application/schema+json" {{ schema_url }}</code></pre>
    <p>
      This documentation URL is referenced in two places in the
      greeting endpoint response:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        In the response body, at
        <code>_links.self.profile</code> &mdash; identifying the
        contract that the response conforms to.
      </li>
      <li>
        In the HTTP <code>Link</code> response header, with
        <code>rel="profile"</code>,
        <code>rel="describedBy"</code>, and
        <code>rel="documentation"</code> &mdash; providing
        machine-discoverable pointers to this documentation and the
        JSON Schema.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The parent of this page is the relations directory at
      <code>{{ parent_url }}</code>, which lists all custom link
      relation types defined by the v1 CBRWS API.
    </p>
  </section>
</main>

